Aye, you have to remember, nothing stays the same forever.  We live in a state of flux.  It wasn't all that long ago that laws had to be passed <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> requiring</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that children between certain ages attended school, because otherwise they would be out working on the family farm, in mines, in factories, etc. rather then allowed the priviledge of sitting down and learning the infamous three R's, &quot;Reading wRiting and aRithmetic&quot;.<br>
<br>
Do you know where the idea of women *not* working, but instead just sitting at home looking after the house, comes from?  The upper class, which was the only class that could afford for the man to support his wife, rather then both husband and wife working to support the family.  The middle class adopted this as a status symbol...&quot;Oh, they're well off, his wife doesn't have to work, she stays at home&quot;.<br>
<br>
Frankly, I don't really care if the mother works, or the father works, or both work...whats important is, how is that child being raised?  Is the child loved and cared for?  Does it have limits that its not allowed to exceed (an important factor that all too many parents seem to ignore these days)?  Is the child encouraged to do and be all they can do and be?  Does that child know it is loved?  Does that chiuld know that there is a place called &quot;home&quot;, and that home is, as someone else once put, &quot;the place that when you have to go there, they have to take you in&quot;.<br>
<br>
You can't define a good parent, mother or father (and I agree with Aldrin that there is a difference between being a male or female parent, and being a Dad or Mom), in terms of whether or not they work, how many hours a day they manage to spend with their child, what items they do or don't purchase for their child.  Someone can be a single mom struggling to subsist on a welfare check, and be a thousands time better parent then someone with a 6-digit salary and all the worldly goods you can imagine.  The reverse is also true.  Because its not the hours, not the objects, not the wage...its the attitude.<br>
<br>
My Mom died when I was 11.  My Dad had a rough few years of grieving before he got his life back together, and resumed being a Dad and not just a male parent and provider of groceries.  In retrospect, there are things he could have done better.  There are things he could have done much, much worse.  In retrospect, my Dad is a darn cool Dad, and I am very proud of him, and of the person he's raised me to be.<br>
